From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: BIP157/BIP158 conformance suite
Date: Sun, 24 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] wasabi: anchor height-one filters to genesis header

BIP157 cfheaders responses include the filter header immediately before
the requested range. For a range starting at height 1, that previous
header is the genesis block filter header, not uint256.Zero.

The P2P compact-filter PR initialized the local filter-header chain with
the genesis filter, but still special-cased start height 1 to zero in
both cfheaders validation and cfilter validation. That makes a conforming
peer look malicious as soon as it answers the first getcfheaders request.

Use zero only for a range that starts at height 0. All later ranges,
including height 1, must use the locally stored previous filter header.

---
diff --git a/WalletWasabi/BitcoinP2p/CompactFilterBehavior.cs b/WalletWasabi/BitcoinP2p/CompactFilterBehavior.cs
index 40f4547..b953cb4 100644
--- a/WalletWasabi/BitcoinP2p/CompactFilterBehavior.cs
+++ b/WalletWasabi/BitcoinP2p/CompactFilterBehavior.cs
@@ -230,9 +230,9 @@ public class CompactFilterBehavior(
 
 		// For the first filter, we need the previous filter header
 		// This comes from either the shared state (last emitted) or the filter header chain
-		var prevFilterHeader = startHeight == 1
+		var prevFilterHeader = startHeight == 0
 			? uint256.Zero
 			: synchronizationState.GetExpectedFilterHeader(startHeight - 1);
 
 		if (prevFilterHeader is null)
 		{
@@ -597,7 +597,7 @@ public class CompactFilterBehavior(
 
 		private bool TryGetPreviousFilterHeader(uint startHeight, [NotNullWhen(true)] out uint256? header)
 		{
-			header = startHeight == 1
+			header = startHeight == 0
 				? uint256.Zero
 				: _filterHeaderChain[startHeight - 1]?.BlockFilterHeader;
 
